This is why Lord of The Spirits is so good, Fr. Stephen de Young makes sure to always give the geopolitical context of every Biblical bit, e.g. how the description of Goliath's bronze armor is important due to breakdown of imperial trade routes making bronze production impossible

I.e. you need copper from Cyprus and tin from Afghanistan so after the Bronze Age collapse bronze became this forgotten technology associated with secret knowledge and the Nephilim. My favorite bit was when he described most of the O.T. basically taking place in a "Mad Max" world

Apparently Chesterton's "The Napoleon of Notting Hill" was also the favorite novel of Michael Collins, the Irish nationalist. Collins was "fanatically attached" to it. Supposedly Lloyd George gave a copy to every member of his cabinet so they could understand Collins' mind better

It came out when Collins was still in his formative years so some people online speculate that it directly inspired his revolutionary Irish nationalism. You wouldn't associate Chesterton with this stuff, but it seems (like Don Quixote proved) literature does influence real life.
Can you expand with your thoughts?
Chesterton was a great man in every way, you can never say enough good things about him
